# Dictionary Architecture

## File Structure

- **`types/dictionary.ts`** — All section types and the composed `Dictionary` type
- **`content/shared.ts`** — Non-translatable config: `siteName`, `siteDescription`, `url`, `contact`, `social`, `images`. Never hardcode these.
- **`content/navigation.ts`** — Single source of truth for nav: label + href together, keyed by locale
- **`content/dictionaries/<section>.ts`** — One file per section (e.g. `faq.ts`, `work.ts`); each exports a const object with `en` and `es` keys
- **`content/dictionaries/index.ts`** — Composes all section dicts into `dictionaries: Record<Locale, Dictionary>`
- **`lib/dictionaries/get<Section>Dict.ts`** — One getter per section: `export function get<Section>Dict(locale: Locale)`
- **`lib/dictionaries/index.ts`** — Re-exports all getters via `export * from "./get<Section>Dict"`

## Type Conventions (`types/dictionary.ts`)

Each section has its own named type. Sections with lists also define an item type:

```typescript
// Simple item type + section type
export type FaqItem = {
    question: string
    answer: string
}

export type FaqDict = {
    title: string
    badge?: string           // optional label above heading
    description?: string
    items: FaqItem[]
    ctaTitle?: string        // optional CTA block at bottom of section
    ctaDescription?: string
    cta?: string
    ctaHref?: string
}
```

All section types are composed into `Dictionary`:

```typescript
export type Dictionary = {
    hero: HeroDict
    about: AboutDict
    services: ServicesDict
    work: WorkDict
    testimonials: TestimonialsDict
    faq: FaqDict
    pricing: PricingDict
    ctaBanner: CtaBannerDict
    contact: ContactDict
    footer: FooterDict
    form: FormDict
    common: CommonDict
    errors: ErrorsDict
    metadata: MetadataDict
}
```

## Data Shape (`content/dictionaries/<section>.ts`)

```typescript
import type { FaqDict } from "@/types/dictionary"

export const faqDict = {
    en: {
        title: "Frequently Asked Questions",
        badge: "FAQ",
        items: [ ... ],
    } satisfies FaqDict,
    es: {
        title: "Preguntas Frecuentes",
        badge: "FAQ",
        items: [ ... ],
    } satisfies FaqDict,
} as const
```

- Use `satisfies <SectionDict>` on each locale object — catches type errors while preserving literal types
- Use `as const` on the export — keeps string literals narrow

## Wiring (`content/dictionaries/index.ts`)

Import each section dict and spread into both locale records:

```typescript
import { faqDict } from "./faq"

export const dictionaries: Record<Locale, Dictionary> = {
    en: { ..., faq: faqDict.en },
    es: { ..., faq: faqDict.es },
}
```

## Getter (`lib/dictionaries/get<Section>Dict.ts`)

```typescript
import { faqDict } from "@/content/dictionaries/faq"
import type { Locale } from "@/types/locale"

export function getFaqDict(locale: Locale) {
    return faqDict[locale]
}
```

Then re-export from `lib/dictionaries/index.ts`:

```typescript
export * from "./getFaqDict"
```

## Usage in Pages

Import only the getters you need via the barrel:

```typescript
import { getHeroDict, getFaqDict, getWorkDict } from "@/lib/dictionaries"

export default function HomePage({ locale }: { locale: Locale }) {
    const hero = getHeroDict(locale)
    const faq  = getFaqDict(locale)
    return (
        <>
            <BriefHero dict={hero} />
            <BriefFaq dict={faq} />
        </>
    )
}
```

## Rules

1. **Navigation** — Always use `content/navigation.ts`. Never split labels and hrefs.
2. **Layout (Navbar/Footer)** — Use `getNavigationDict(locale)` and `getFooterDict(locale)`. Do not pull the full dict.
3. **Shared config** — Brand name, contact, social, URLs always come from `content/shared.ts`. Never hardcode.
4. **Add a new section** — Four steps: add types to `types/dictionary.ts` → create `content/dictionaries/<section>.ts` → wire in `content/dictionaries/index.ts` → create `lib/dictionaries/get<Section>Dict.ts` and re-export.
5. **Optional fields** — Use `?` for `badge`, `description`, `cta`, `ctaHref`, `ctaTitle`, `ctaDescription`. Never require copy that might not be needed.
6. **Item types** — Any section with a list of objects gets a named item type (e.g. `FaqItem`, `WorkItem`, `TestimonialItem`).
